Mac  The C# Template Project | Chris F Carroll','','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/p1319/run-asp-net-mvc4-on-mono-monodevelop-on-mac-the-c-template-project','69.28.199.10','2014-01-13 23:23:27','2014-01-13 23:23:27','[&#8230;]      This entry was posted in Code and tagged mono. Bookmark the permalink.    &larr; Using Castle Windsor DI for controllers in an Asp.Net WebApi Project Just Enough Design Upfront? How to draw the line between enough and too much &rarr; [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(812,1510,'Ben Parsons','ben@bpulse.co.uk','http://www.bpulse.co.uk','94.7.105.27','2014-01-30 00:28:40','2014-01-30 00:28:40','It works, it works! Bless you Chis F Carroll, I\'ve been chasing between blogs and StackOverflow for an hour with small progress, and this just works!',0,'1','','',0,0),(813,1510,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.1.185.179','2014-01-30 12:12:16','2014-01-30 12:12:16','well thank you ;-)',0,'1','','',0,2),(814,1510,'Curtis Schlak','curtis_schlak@yahoo.com','http://curtis.schlak.com','99.63.24.13','2014-02-05 05:19:19','2014-02-05 05:19:19','Just wanted you to know that I posted updated instruction for ASP.NET MVC 5 on Mono 3.2.6 over at <a href=\"http://curtis.schlak.com/2014/02/04/setup-asp-net-mvc-4-on-monodevelop-4.2.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Setup ASP.NET MVC 5 on MonoDevelop 4.2</a>. In case you\'re interested. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(815,1510,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.1.185.179','2014-02-05 09:58:43','2014-02-05 09:58:43','Excellent! Thank you, \nChris',0,'1','','',814,2),(816,1510,'Anthony','social@zrate.com','http://www.zrate.com','108.68.81.3','2014-02-06 04:47:42','2014-02-06 04:47:42','Looks good!\nI wonder if the IT guy used this on the freight app?',0,'1','','',0,0),(817,1528,'QUIYENGA, FILBERT','quiyengabf@gmail.com','','209.95.36.12','2015-05-04 05:05:41','2015-05-04 05:05:41','HELLO\n\nI BEG FOR HELP, I HAVE DONE INSTALLATION OF WINDOWS 8.1 ON MACBOOK OS X MOUNTAIN LION, BUT THE OS X, IS NOT FOUND WHEN I SWITCH ON THE PC AGAIN AND WHEN  THE WINDOWS 7 0R 8.1 IS ON, THERE IS NO SOUND.',0,'1','','',0,0),(818,1528,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.2.49.176','2015-05-05 19:41:45','2015-05-05 19:41:45','Hi Filbert,\nIf you installed Windows 8 on your Mac using BootCamp then you want to find the BootCamp control panel to boot back into OS X -- for instance <a href=\"http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/switch-between-windows-and-os-x-with-macs-boot-cam.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.dummies.com/how-to/content/switch-between-windows-and-os-x-with-macs-boot-cam.html</a>\n\nIf you installed Windows 8 on your Mac WITHOUT using BootCamp then you might have deleted the Mac partition and OS X and everything on it.\n\nThe last thing you can try is, rebooting the machine and holding down the  <b>Option </b>  key.  See <a href=\"https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT201255\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT201255</a>',0,'1','','',0,2),(819,1558,'Rob Vens','rob.vens@reflektis.com','http://www.robvens.com','82.72.69.196','2014-02-06 10:44:50','2014-02-06 10:44:50','Thanks Chris for discussing this important issue. As you, I see many modellers wrestle with this. However, the direction you seem to have taken (stateless interfaces and public state if I may summarise this way) although well argued, still seems unnecessary. I know (as you do, as I deduce from your sound reasoning) that it counters the rule of OO design as well, but that is not the source of my unease. That source is that the kind of solutions you create in this manner are not innovative or supportive for new ways of integrating business and IT. They reflect the \"old\" way of doing business. As you explain: with documents and long-running processes detached from those documents. Could you agree that it is possible and potentially rewarding to model the business in a different way, more in line with the actual complexity of intertwined businesses and customers, for which the \"traditional\" rules of encapsulation would apply because there is no other way to model all that complexity in a manner that is flexible and manageable? And that these models would provide real and even much added value?',0,'1','','',0,0),(820,1558,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.1.185.179','2014-02-06 13:56:04','2014-02-06 13:56:04','Hi Rob, \nThanks for dropping by! Do please say a bit more - or point me to a link? - about new ways of integrating business and IT.  I agree that my line of argument leads to something that is not innovative. But I do think it supports moving forwards, because the best starting point for modelling the businesss evolution from today to tomorrow is  a model of today\'s business. And the innovation that gets us to tomorrow has to happen first in the enterprise architecture & the business processes before we express in application design & code, doesnt it?\n\nDo you think the description Ive given of the way a \"typical business\" (as if there were such a thing!) works is wrong? If so, then yes Id agree with modelling it differently. Ive based the above largely on small/medium businesses where Ive worked the past few years. \n\nI think modelling the *actual* complexity of intertwined businesses and customers is definitely right. \"Model whats *actually* there\" is imho the OO prime directive. Either that or match the users mental model\"\nChris',0,'1','','',0,2),(821,1614,'Lukas','yo@we.com','','79.211.78.33','2014-10-23 20:24:08','2014-10-23 20:24:08','Thank you very much! I almost gave up on that!',0,'1','','',0,0),(822,1614,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.2.49.176','2014-10-23 20:30:19','2014-10-23 20:30:19',':-)',0,'1','','',821,2),(823,84,'Mark','marklennard@mac.com','','92.237.119.178','2012-03-26 07:39:05','2012-03-26 07:39:05','Hi, Any chance you know how I can swap the @ and \"keys round on a apple wired keyboard that I have plugged into Windows 7??  I tried sharp keys but did not seem to work?',0,'1','','',0,0),(824,84,'Chris','chris@birchwood-church.org','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','212.140.246.20','2012-03-29 14:22:29','2012-03-29 14:22:29','You have to follow the link to the Microsoft Keyboard Layout Creator to do it.  If you\'ve got an hour to play with it, it\'s not too hard. \nThe one I did is for UK keyboard, I take it you\'re on a US keyboard and want just those 2 keys done?',0,'1','','',823,2),(825,1708,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.2.49.176','2014-12-11 21:57:38','2014-12-11 21:57:38','PPPS\nIf you want to do service architecture well, there is an excellent 4 pager at <a href=\"http://www.tigerteam.dk/2014/micro-services-its-not-only-the-size-that-matters-its-also-how-you-use-them-part-1/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.tigerteam.dk/2014/micro-services-its-not-only-the-size-that-matters-its-also-how-you-use-them-part-1/</a>. \nIt is the best introduction to implementing service architecture that I have seen; it talks through how to do it wrong and how do it right; and helps you through the key transition in thinking, from synchronous to asynchronous.',0,'1','','',0,2),(826,1807,'Greg Gill','brisbanedatarecovery@gmail.com','http://brisbanedatarecovery.com.au/','103.25.251.15','2017-03-02 02:46:43','2017-03-02 02:46:43','Good points. Just amazing work!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(827,1847,'Krish','krishratnam@gmail.com','','64.231.207.157','2015-09-23 03:33:27','2015-09-23 03:33:27','I followed the instructions above. I created sparse bundle file. But when I click on the sparsebundle file, Time Machine Backups appears in finder for 0.5 minute and then disappears and I am do not see the disk in  Time Machine either. I did install Fuse OX NTFS-3G. Did I miss something? My Mac version is 10.6.8.',0,'1','','',0,0),(828,1847,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.2.49.176','2015-09-23 13:51:13','2015-09-23 13:51:13','Hi Krish,\nInteresting. It could be quite hard to track down why the sparsebundle image unmounts like that. My first guess is that it\'s to do with your OS X version and that 10.6 doesn\'t want the com.apple.TimeMachine.MachineID.plist file inside the sparsebundle like later versions do.  \nSo, try:\n1) Manual create the sparsebundle image in Disk Utility\n2) Double click it.\n3) If it stays mounted, then open Time Machine and see if appears in your list of disks to save to.\nOR: \nTry the instructions in http://code.stephenmorley.org/articles/time-machine-on-a-network-drive/ from about step 4 (ignoring the network drive stuff) and see if that works better?\nThose are my first ideas, anyway.',0,'1','','',827,2),(829,1847,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','80.2.49.176','2015-09-23 13:55:00','2015-09-23 13:55:00','This post in the Apple forums <a href=\"https://discussions.apple.com/thread/2135602\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://discussions.apple.com/thread/2135602<a></a> suggests that it\'s a problem with specific OS X versions</a>',0,'1','','',827,2),(830,1847,'Krish','krishratnam@gmail.com','','64.231.207.157','2015-09-24 13:32:12','2015-09-24 13:32:12','Hi Chris, Thanks for the suggestion. I tried following the instructions on the website you cited. The end result is still the same. The sparsebundle created using those steps mounts and stays mounted for few seconds and then disappears. It does not show up on Time Machine during that short duration either.\n\nOne thing I did not share with you is that I had to install NTFS-3G to make my NTFS hard drive writable. Do you think it has to do with this \"custom\" Sharing and Permisssions I have on this drive?\n\nMany Thanks,\nKrish',0,'1','','',0,0),(831,1847,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','50.159.73.46','2015-09-28 19:16:33','2015-09-28 19:16:33','The Apple Forums post suggests that it\'s a problem for specific OS X versions so upgrading a version or so might help. I guess that so long as you have at least read & write permissions on the drive, the \'custom\' settings don\'t matter much. Sorry I haven\'t got anything more helpful.',0,'1','','',830,2),(832,1847,'Saurabh','ntweat@ntweat.com','','69.255.29.66','2017-08-13 01:14:09','2017-08-13 01:14:09','Hi\n\nI tried this a few times\nand everytime it created small drives\nI have a 1 TB external with 600 GB free\nI am trying to get 500 GB, it only gives 100GB\n\nany solutions?',0,'1','','',0,0),(833,1847,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','82.2.9.151','2017-08-15 16:19:33','2017-08-15 16:19:33','Hi Saurabh, there are 2 things that might cause this: \n1) Did you use the parameter for disk size, e.g.  tmMakeImage 500GB\n2) If you did, then everything is fine and it is normal that you see a much smaller disk than you asked for. When you create a sparsebundle, the disk space is not used until you actually use it. Start doing your backups and you will find that space used eventually grows.',0,'1','','',832,2),(834,1879,'Was ist Post-Agilitt? Context over Convention - the conventic way. Eine Begriffsdefinition. - Conventic - Standardisierte Software-Entwicklung &amp; Beratung','','http://conventic.com/was-ist-post-agilitaet/','212.227.119.15','2017-04-25 08:05:25','2017-04-25 08:05:25','[&#8230;] wiederum haben ein &#8222;post-agiles Manifesto&#8220; erarbeitet, dieser lautet, vereinfacht ausgedrckt: wenn es funktioniert, tu es. Wenn es nicht [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(835,1911,'The Morning Brew - Chris Alcock &raquo; The Morning Brew #2060','','http://blog.cwa.me.uk/2016/03/29/the-morning-brew-2060/','212.227.109.184','2016-03-29 08:19:40','2016-03-29 08:19:40','[&#8230;] IIS Express : Run a child web application in a virtual directory under a parent application &#8211; Chris F Carroll [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(836,1931,'We feel free because we lack the very link to articulate our unfreedom. - Magnus Udbjrg','','http://udbjorg.net/2016/10/06/feel-free-lack-link-articulate-unfreedom/','137.135.129.144','2016-10-06 14:28:27','2016-10-06 14:28:27','[&#8230;] Conways Law &amp; Distributed Working. Some Comments &amp; Experience | Chris F Carroll [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(837,1988,'Rus','russ.smirnov@outlook.com','','108.14.10.205','2017-11-22 11:25:03','2017-11-22 11:25:03','This is good! One note -- nobody uses varchar in Postgres (it is simply a text type with a length constraint). Unlike MS SQL, text columns are stored directly inside the table and thus there is no real reason to use varchar for strings; just make everything \'text\'.',0,'1','','',0,0),(838,1988,'Chris F Carroll','chris.carroll@unforgettable.me.uk','http://www.cafe-encounter.net/','82.2.9.151','2017-11-22 11:53:46','2017-11-22 11:53:46','Why thankyou! Noted.',0,'1','','',837,2),(839,2080,'The Morning Brew - Chris Alcock &raquo; The Morning Brew #2409','','http://blog.cwa.me.uk/2017/08/21/the-morning-brew-2409/','217.160.63.97','2017-08-21 07:10:04','2017-08-21 07:10:04','[&#8230;] [RequireClaim()] Attribute for Claims-based Authorization Asp.Net Core &#8211; Chris F Carroll [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0),(840,2080,'Brent J Arias','barias@axiscode.com','','70.98.97.180','2017-08-21 20:15:18','2017-08-21 20:15:18','Back around 2013 I discovered that the RoleAttribute does indeed match against claims.  Unfortunately I don\'t recall if it was MVC or Web API I had done my research and testing with (and it may have been OWIN).  I\'d suspect that behavior has continued to the present.',0,'1','','',0,0),(841,2158,'The Morning Brew - Chris Alcock &raquo; The Morning Brew #2435','','http://blog.cwa.me.uk/2017/10/04/the-morning-brew-2435-2/','217.160.63.97','2017-10-04 06:56:34','2017-10-04 06:56:34','[&#8230;] Three Historical Definitions of the Open/Closed Principle and a Claim that it&#8217;s Pointless &#8211; Chris F Carroll [&#8230;]',0,'1','','pingback',0,0);
